Use TensorFlow Datasets to Download Data

In previous notebooks, we've downloaded our food images from google storage.

There's another way to get datasets ready for TensorFlow.

The most popular datasets in machine learning world (often used as a benchmark), can be accessed through TensorFlow Datasets (TFDS).

What is TensorFlow Datasets?

A place for prepeared and ready-to-use machine learning datasets.

Why use TensorFlow Datasets?

  • Load data already in Tensors
  • Practice on well established datasets
  • Experiment with different data loading techniques (like we're going to use in this notebook)
  • Experiment with new TensorFlow features quickly (such as mixed precision training)

Why not use TensorFlow Datasets?

  • If the data is static (aka they don't change, like real-world datasets)
  • Might not be suited to your problems (but great for experimentation)

Looks like our desired dataset exists! To access it, we use tfds.load() method.

We'll have to pass a few parameters to let it know what we're after:

  • name (str): the target dataset (e.g. "food101")
  • split (list,optional): which split of the data we're after (e.g. "train" or "test")
    • the split parameter is quite tricky. Here's the documentation.
  • shuffle_files (bool): To whether shuffle or not on the files. Default is False.
  • as_supervised (bool): True to download data samples in tuple format (data, label) or False for dictionary format.
  • with_info (bool): True to download dataset metadata (labels, number of samples, etc)

Create preprocessing functions for our data

In previous notebooks, when our images were in folder format, we used the format tf.keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory() to load them.

This makes it format ready. But from downloading from TensorFlow Datasets, there are a couple of preprocessing steps we need to do before it is ready.

Currently, our data is:

  • In unit8 data type
  • Comprised of all different sized tensors
  • Pixel value not scaled

While models like data as:

  • In float32 data type
  • All the same sized tensors
  • Scaled to 0 to 1

To take care of these, we'll create a preprocess_img() function which:

  • Resizes all tensors to a specific size using tf.image.resize()
  • Converts an input image tensor's current datatype to tf.float32 using tf.cast()

Note: Pretrained EfficientNetBX models in tf.keras.applications.efficientnet have rescaling built in. But many others need to be rescaled manually, which can be incorporated into preprocess_img() function. Or in model via tf.keras.layers.Rescaling layer.

In[23]:
# make a function for preprocessing images
def preprocess_img(image, label, img_shape=224):
    '''
    Converts image datatype from 'unit8' -> 'float32' and reshapes image to:
    [img_shape,img_shape,colour_channels]
    '''
    image=tf.image.resize(image, [img_shape,img_shape]) # reshape to img_shape
    return tf.cast(image, tf.float32), label # return (float32_image, label) tuple

Our preprocess_img() function above takes image and label as input, as our data is a tuple when loaded in vie Tensor Dataset, and is hardwired to see the 2 variables due to our use of as_supervised=True. (Even if you only wanted to change the image OR the label, not both)

Let's try our function out on a target image.

In[]:

Batch and prepare datasets

First, we need to compute in batches to create memory efficiency.

We'll turn 101,000 images into batches of 32 image and label pairs. We will use methods such as tf.data API.

Resource: When loading data in the most performant way possible, here's a documentation for reading if needed: Better performance with the tf.data API

We'll be using:

  • map() - maps a predefined function to a target dataset (e.g. preprocess_img() to our image tensors)
  • shuffle() - randomly shuffles elements in a dataset. Uses buffer_size (ideally, buffer_size is equal to size of dataset, though may have implications on memory)
  • batch() - turns elements of a target dataset into batches (size is defined by parameter batch_size)
  • prefretch() - prepares subsequent batches of data whilst other batches of data are being computed (improves data loading speed, though costs more memory)
  • Extra: cache() - Catches (saves them for later) elements in a target dataset, saving loading time (only works for small enough dataset that can fit into memory)

Things to note:

  • You can't batch tensors of different shapes (e.g. different image size - and must be the same size)
  • shuffle() keeps a buffer of a number of images to be shuffled while data is being used, ideally this number would be all of the samples in your training set. If you training set is large, buffer might not fit in memory. (A fairly large number like 1,000 or 10,000 is usually suffice for shuffling - what it does is shuffling an area of the data, at an area where the model is training, while outside stays the same)
  • For methods with the num_parallel_calls parameter available (such as map()), setting it to num_parallel_calls=tf.data.AUTOTUNE will parallelize preprocessing and significantly improve speed.
    • Aka, the computer will run multiple images simultaneously between each other, rather than doing them in a single file order/queue (which causes bottlenecking). AUTOTUNE will choose the optimal number of cells to run in parallel, based on your CPU/GPU hardware, rather than you having to guess it yourself.
  • Can't use cache() unless your dataset can fit in memory.

It's alot, but once we've coded below, it'll make sense.

We're going through things in the following order:

Original dataset (e.g. train_data) -> map() -> shuffle() -> batch() -> prefetch() -> PrefetchDataset

This is like saying:

Hey computer - map this preprocessing function across our training dataset, then shuffle a number of elements before batching them together, and make sure you prepare new batches (prefetch) whilst the model is looking through the current batch.

What happens when you use prefetching (which are faster) vs. what happens when you don't use prefetching (slower). Source: Page 422 of Hands-On Machine Learning with Scikit-Learn, Keras and TensorFlow Book.

In[61]:
# Map preprocesing function to training data (and paralellize)
train_data = train_data.map(map_func=preprocess_img, num_parallel_calls=tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
# Shuffle train_data and turn it into batches and prefetch it (load it faster)
train_data = train_data.shuffle(buffer_size=1000).batch(batch_size=32).prefetch(buffer_size=tf.data.AUTOTUNE)

# Map preprocessing function to test data
test_data = test_data.map(preprocess_img, num_parallel_calls=tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
# Turn test data into batches (don't need to shuffle)
test_data = test_data.batch(32).prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)

Note: You can get away without calling the prefetch() method on the end of your datasets. However you'd probably see significantly slower data loading speeds when building a model. So most of your dataset input pipeline should end with a call to prefetch().

Create modelling callbacks

Due to how large the data is, it's essential to have modelling callbacks to track model training logs, or being chckpointed (saved) after various training milestones.

To do so, we'll use the following callbacks:

  • tf.keras.callbacks.TensorBoard() - allows us to keep track of model's training history for later inspection
  • tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint() - saves our model's progress at any interval, where we can load it and reuse/continue training without having to redo it from start.
    • Checpoint is also useful if we feel like we want to go back to a particular epoch, and revert it to that previous stae, rather than it's current fully trained self.

                                                      save_weights_only=True, # only save model weights (not all the layers etc.)
                                                      verbose=0) # don't print out whether or not the model is being saved

Setup mixed precision training

We've learnt a little bit about it with 06 homework.

TensorFlow normally uses float32, aka uses 32 bits to compute each weight value. This is a limit that GPU memories can handle. But we got mixed precision.

This uses a mix of float16 and float32 to make better use of GPU memory, as it uses half the bits (16 bits) for each weight value.

This mixture of use allows the computer to use less memory wherever possible to run faster (aka, more tensors can be computed simultaneously, increasing training speed).

More info can be read at: TensorFlow mixed precision guide

Let's see how mixed precision training is implemented on TensorFlow.

First we'll import the API and then use the set_global_policy() method to set the dtype policy to 'mixed_float16'.

In[64]:
# Turn on mixed precision training
from tensorflow.keras import mixed_precision
mixed_precision.set_global_policy(policy='mixed_float16') # set global policy to mixed precision

Build feature extraction model

Let's start building a model.

Due to how large the dataset is, we're going to move towards fine-tuning an existing pretrained model. (EfficientNetB0).

Before fine-tuning, let's set up the feature extraction model first. As a refresher of the steps to build one:

  • Use EfficientNetB0 from tf.keras.applications pre-trained on ImageNet as our base model.
    • We'll download this without the top layers using include_top=False parameter so we can create our own output layers.
  • Freeze the base model layers, so we can utilize pre-trained weights/patterns of the original model.
  • Put together the input, base model, pooling and output layers in a Functional API model
  • Compile the Functional model using the Adam optimizer and Sparse Categorical Crossentropy as the loss function (since our labels aren't one-hot encoded - and only need the index value of highest probability)
  • Fit the model for 3 epochs using the TensorBoard and ModelCheckpoint callbacks

Note: Due to mixed precision training - the model's output layer must stay as dtype=float32. For example, layers.Activatioin('softmax', dtype=tf.float32). This insures the outputs of our model are returned back to the float 32 data type, which is more numerically stable than float16. Very crucial for loss calculation, as numbers tend to be extremely big, and float16 is not able to accomodate it, often returning a value of inf.

Mixed precision is turned on via the labeled 3 lines of code

In[68]:
from tensorflow.keras import layers

# create base model
input_shape=(224,224,3)
base_model=tf.keras.applications.EfficientNetB0(include_top=False)
base_model.trainable=False # freeze base model layer weights

# Create functional API model
inputs = layers.Input(shape=input_shape, name='input_layer')
# Note: EfficientNetBx - has built in rescaling. However if your base model doesn't have that, include:
# x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(x)
x = base_model(inputs, training=False) # set base_model to inference mode, where normalization, dropout etc. weights that influence other weights are frozen
x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D(name='pooling_layer')(x)
x = layers.Dense(len(class_names))(x) # want one output neuron per class (making 101 neurons)

outputs = layers.Activation('softmax', dtype=tf.float32, name='softmax_float32')(x) # remember that output MUST be float32 to work
model = tf.keras.Model(inputs,outputs)

# compile the model
model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', # use only when labels are not one-hot encoded
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

Checking layer dtype policies (are we using mixed precision?)

We said how mixed precision API will automatically change the layers' dtype policy to whatever global dtype we set it to (aka. mixed_float16).

We can check this by iterating through the model layers, and check the dtype and dtype_police.

In[70]:
# check the dtype_policy sttributes of layers in our model
for layer in model.layers:
    print(layer.name, layer.trainable, layer.dtype, layer.dtype_policy) # check the dtype policy of layers

input_layer True float32 <Policy "float32">
efficientnetb0 False float32 <Policy "mixed_float16">
pooling_layer True float32 <Policy "mixed_float16">
dense True float32 <Policy "mixed_float16">
softmax_float32 True float32 <Policy "float32">

Looking at the above, the variables are from left to right:

  • layer.name (str): A readable name for humans - can be definied by the name parameter on contruction
  • layer.trainable (bool): Whether or not the layer is trainable
  • layer.dtype: The data type the layer stores its variables in
  • layer.dtype_policy: The data type the layer computes in

Note: A layer can have a dtype of float32 and a dtype policy of 'mixed_float16' because it stores its variables in float32 (more numerically stable), however it computes in float16 (which is faster).

We can check the same details for our model's base model.

Load and evaluate checkpoint weights

We can load it in and evaluate our model's checkpoints by:

  1. Recreating a new instance of our model called created_model by turning our original model creation code into a function called create_model().
  2. Compiling our created_model with the same loss, optimizer and metrics as the original model (every time you create a new model, you must compile it).
  3. Calling the load_weights() method on our created_model and passing it the path to where our checkpointed weights are stored.
  4. Calling evaluate() on created_model with loaded weights and saving the results.
  5. Comparing the created_model results to the previous model results (should be the exact same or extremely close).

A reminder, checkpoints are helpful when you perform experiments on a model. If the experiment turned out to make the model even worse, you can always revert it back to when you haven't done the experiment.

Note: tf.keras.clone_model was previously used in the loading model part, but came with some errors. There is a github discussion from the creator of he course regarding it.

In[]:
# 1. Create a function to recreate the original model
def create_model():
    # create a base model
    input_shape = (224,224,3)
    base_model = tf.keras.applications.efficientnet.EfficientNetB0(include_top=False)
    base_model.trainable=False # freeze base model layers

    # create functional model
    inputs = layers.Input(shape=input_shape,name='input_layer')
    # x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(x) # < use if model doesn't come with rescaling
    x = base_model(inputs,training=False) # set base_model to inference mode
    x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D(name='pooling_layer')(x)
    x = layers.Dense(len(class_names))(x) # one output neuron per class
    # output layer must be float32
    outputs = layers.Activation('softmax',dtype=tf.float32,name='softmax_float32')(x)
    model = tf.keras.Model(inputs,outputs)

    return model

# 2. Create and compile a new version of the original model (new weights)
created_model = create_model()
created_model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                      optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(),
                      metrics=['accuracy'])

# 3. Load the saved weights
created_model.load_weights(checkpoint_path)

# 4. Evaluate the model with loaded weights
results_created_model_with_loaded_weights = created_model.evaluate(test_data)

A couple more callbacks

We're about to begin fine tuning a 200-layered model on over 100,000 images. Which will take a very long time. This may take a couple of hours, or even 2-3 days from the DeepFood paper (which is the baseline we're wanting to beat).

Question: When should you stop training?

Ideally when the model stops improving. But with the nature of deep learning, it can be hard to know exactly when a model will stop improving. Fortunately, Earlystopping callback solves this issue.

The callback monitors the specified model performance metric (e.g. val_loss). When it stops improving for a specified number of epochs, training is automatically halted.

Using EarlyStopping and ModelCheckpoint callbacks, we could keep our model training for an unlimited number of epochs until it stops improving.

Let's set both of these up to monitor model's val_loss.

In[88]:
# setup earlystopping callback to stop training if model's val_loss doesn't improve for 3 epochs
early_stopping=tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', # watch the val loss metric
                                                patience=3) # if val loss doesn't improve for 3 epochs in a row, stop training

# create ModelCheckpoint callback to save best model during fine-tuning
checkpoint_path='fine_tune_checkpoints/'
model_checkpoint=tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(checkpoint_path,
                                                    save_best_only=True,
                                                    monitor='val_loss')

When training large models, EarlyStopping and ModelCheckpoint are absolutely essential to familiarize with.

Another callback we want to implement is: ReduceLROnPlateau.

You know how learning rate is the most important model hyperparameter there is? Well the ReduceLROnPlateau callback helps to tune the learning rate for you.

Like the other 2 callback metrics, ReduceLROnPlateau also tracks a specific metric. If such metric stops improving, it reduces the learning rate by a specified factor (e.g. dividing learning rate by 10).

Question: Why the lowering of LR?

Analogy, if you got a coin at the back of the couch and you want to grab it, how are your motor skills changing during the grab? The further you are, the more forceful you are to pushing and moving through.

Then the closer you are, the more refined and smaller your movements are. Because if you move too suddenly and quickly like you did when pushing your way down, the coin may likely disappear from view too quickly and you need to search for it again.

Our model performance is similar to that. As our model gets closer and closer to it's ideal performance (convergence), then we want it to learn less and less, therefore making smaller and smaller movements.

To do this, we have the instance ReduceLROnPlateau callback to monitor validation loss.

Once validation loss stops improving for two or more epochs, we'll reduce LR by factor of 5. (e.g. 0.1 becomes 0.02).

We don't want LR to be too small, so will set a 1e-7 limit or else we get no movement from the model's LR.

In[]:
# creating learning rate reduction callback
reduce_lr = tf.keras.callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss',
                                                 factor=0.2, # multiply lr by 0.2
                                                 patience=2,
                                                 verbose=1, # prints out when lr is going down
                                                 min_lr=1e-7)

Before starting, we have to recompile the model since we've made changes to it.

We'll use sparse categorical crossentropy as the loss and since we're fine tuning, we'll use a 10x lower LR than the Adam optimizer's 1e-3 default.

In[]:
# compile the model
loaded_gs_model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', # use for labels that are not one-hot encoded, but indexed
                        optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(0.0001), # 10x smaller than default
                        metrics=['accuracy'])

Since we're using EarlyStopping, it may stop before reaching 100 epochs.
